transcripts.transcript: Hi, I've been feeling really overwhelmed lately. My final exams are coming up, and I'm just... I can't seem to handle the pressure. It's just... I feel like there's so much riding on these exams. My grades, my future college prospects, my parents' expectations. I'm afraid of letting everyone down, especially myself. I try to study a lot, but the more I study, the more I feel like I'm not doing enough. Sometimes I just freeze and can't absorb anything, and then I get even more anxious. I've tried taking breaks, but then I feel guilty, like I'm wasting precious time. That sounds helpful. I just want to get through this without feeling like I'm drowning. Well, I usually wake up early and start studying right away. I sometimes skip breakfast because I feel like I'm running out of time. I study for hours without taking many breaks. By the evening, I'm completely exhausted, but I still push through, often studying late into the night. I know breakfast is important, but when I'm stressed, I just don't feel hungry. I've heard of the Pomodoro Technique but never tried. I worry that taking so many breaks will distract me even more. I'm willing to give it a try. But how do I deal with the immense pressure? The fear of failure is always looming over me. An opportunity for what? That's a different way to look at it. I've always been so focused on the outcome that I forget to appreciate the process. Thank you for giving me a new perspective. I'll try to keep that in mind as I prepare.
